Fixing Exploits

# Memory Corruptions

Make sure buffer is big enough for overflow to occur into target region

1.  Take control of EIP by overwriting Return address on the stack by padding the large buffer with an appropriate offset
2.  Choose correct return addr instruction, e.g. JMP ESP to redirect the execution flow into our payload

# Cross Compiling

To compile a C code for running in Windows

> i686-w64-mingw32-gcc &lt;C file&gt; -o &lt;Filename.exe&gt;

If the compilation has issues due to WSAStartup, then add the option "-lws2_32" to the back

# Common Modification Guideline

Take note to modify the exploit on mostly the following

- Socket Information (Especially for the reverse shell)
- Return Address exists in the target programme
    - If we have access to our target as an unprivileged user, we can copy the DLLs that we are interested into attacking, and figure out the addresses
        - Use diassembler tools like windbg or msfpescan 
- Change the payload (Shellcode)
- We can test the programme using wine
    - wine &lt;exploit.exe&gt;
    - Attach EBD debugger to it
- For strings data, make sure to calculate the null termination byte 

# Web Exploits 

Considerations to take note:

- HTTP/HTTPS?
- App access: Specific path or route?
- Exploit leverage a pre-auth vuln?
- If no, how does exploit auth to web app?
- How are GET and POST crafted to trigger and exploit vuln?
- Does it rely on default app settings?
- Does oddities disrupt the exploit (e.g. self-signed certs?)

Change context of the code - ip addresses, URLs, credentials, filenames
